Ratio manifesta est: quia media suut propter finem, non finis propter media3 et proinde media fini inservire debent, non finis inservire mediis. against foreign or domestic enemies, to regard Public Utility, the Supreme Law, more than the words and terms of Particular Laws3 since these were made to promote, not to prejudice, Public Utility.

The Public Safety is the End, Laws are the Means3 and the Means must be subservient to the End. And the Prince, who is the principal agent in the making of Laws, must be presumed to think so, and therefore tacitly to consent to whatever is, without his being con- sulted, done for the common safety under manifest necessity.

22. There are many examples of this in history: we will take one from our own annals. The Lord Lieutenant of each Oounty in England has the command of the military force of his County, to be used for necessary purposes within the County3 but with no autho- rity to pass with armed men beyond the boundary of the Oounty.
